🎉 Happy New Year beautiful friends! 2022 has really been about settling into being a new mother and a full-time entrepreneur for me. 
✨
We welcomed our precious son into this world at the end of 2021 after years of trying to conceive. I quit my job in April of 2022 with a new baby and without making enough money to replace my income. I quit before my website was even monetized! And if you don’t know what that means, I basically had no steady income when I quit. 
✨
It might sound like madness to some, I stepped out on absolute faith and trusted that God would see the vision he gave me through. Not only did I monetize my website a few months after I quit my job, I replaced the income of my full-time job a few times over! 
✨
Our son is healthy and thriving and my husband started a new job this year as well. I share this with you as living proof that believing in yourself and the promise of God will always prevail. I am overjoyed and filled with expectant hope as we step into 2023. I know without a shadow of a doubt that this year will be the most bountiful and blessed year for my family and Pink Owl Kitchen yet! 
✨
Thank you to each and every supporter that I have gained on this platform. Some of you feel like extended family members to me and I am beyond grateful for your love and support. Be blessed and encouraged my friends! Here’s to an abundant 2023! 🥂
✨

Happy February and first day of Black History Month! It’s a celebration of Blackness and history all year but this month is a time to highlight excellence! I’m sharing this Buttermilk Pie because it takes my back to visiting my Grandma in Bentonia, Mississippi. She would make buttermilk pie every time we visited, along with baked or fried chicken, collard greens with hog maw, mac and cheese (the black folks kind), and candied yams. We would sit in her small, hot apartment and eat and laugh then us kids would go run around outside while the grown folks played spades and drank beer. My Black Southern roots run deep and my food reflects that in every bite. Happy Black History month y’all! 🖤🤎

Old Fashioned Southern Tea Cakes are an old school southern dessert that’s kind of a cross between a cookie and a cake. They have a soft, cakey center with crispy edges and tastes incredible with coffee, milk, or tea. Tea cakes, like many southern recipes, date back to the days of slavery when enslaved people took what few ingredients they could get their hands on and turned them into something delicious. Every southerner has their own secret way of making tea cakes and everyone’s is the best (but mine really are 😮‍💨).

**recipe below!** Here’s a comfort food classic for ya as we step into cozy season! Southern homemade chicken and dumplings is a classic comfort food dish made with chicken and vegetables cooked in a creamy broth topped with fluffy biscuit dumplings. Recipe below 👇🏽

What you need:
Chicken soup
▢ 6 tablespoons unsalted butter divided
▢ 1 medium yellow onion chopped
▢ 3 stalks celery chopped
▢ 3 medium carrots chopped small
▢ 1 teaspoon garlic powder
▢ ½ teaspoon onion powder
▢ ½ teaspoon dried thyme leaves
▢ Salt and cracked black pepper to taste
▢ ¼ cup all-purpose flour
▢ 4 cups chicken stock
▢ ¼ cup heavy cream
▢ 1, 3 pound rotisserie chicken bones and skin removed, shredded, about 4 cups of chicken
Dumplings
▢ 2 cups all-purpose flour spooned and leveled
▢ 1 tablespoon baking powder
▢ 1 teaspoon salt
▢ ¼ teaspoon black pepper
▢ 4 tablespoons unsalted butter cold, sliced into squares
▢ ⅔ - 1 cup buttermilk cold
▢ Fresh chopped parsley for garnish, optional

How to make it:
1. Cook the vegetables. Cook the veggies in 2 tablespoons of butter over medium-high heat for 3-4 minutes then add the spices.
2. Make the roux. Add 4 tablespoons of butter and the flour and cook while stirring for 2 to 3 minutes.
3. Make the soup. Add the broth, cream, and chicken and simmer.
4. Make the dumplings. Combine the flour, baking powder, salt, butter, and buttermilk in a bowl to create the biscuit dumpling dough.
5. Cook the dumplings. Use a cookie scoop to place dumplings on top of the soup. Cover the pot and simmer the soup until the dumplings are cooked through.
6. Garnish and enjoy! Allow the soup to cool slightly, top with freshly chopped parsley, and ladle into bowls.

WHAT YOU NEED:
For the Cake
▢ 3 cups all-purpose flour (375g) weighed or spooned and leveled

👇🏽recipe below | save for later👇🏽 Do not make another pot of soup, chili, gumbo, or anything for that matter without some of these fluffy, moist, sweet, cornbread muffins on the side! Cornbread is a love language in the South and it makes every meal better!

What you need:
▢ 1 ½ cups all-purpose flour spooned and leveled
▢ ¾ cups yellow cornmeal
▢ ½ cup granulated sugar
▢ 1 tablespoon baking powder
▢ 1 teaspoon salt
▢ 1 ¼ cups whole buttermilk
▢ 1 large egg
▢ 2 tablespoons honey
▢ 6 tablespoons melted unsalted butter

How to make it:
👉🏽Preheat your oven to 350°F. Spray a muffin tin with nonstick cooking spray or line it with cupcake liners and set it aside.
👉🏽whisk together the flour, cornmeal, sugar, baking powder, and salt until combined. In a separate medium mixing bowl, whisk together the buttermilk, egg, and honey until the egg is completely mixed into the other ingredients.
👉🏽Make a well in the center of the flour mixture, and pour the buttermilk mixture into the well. Use a wooden spoon or rubber spatula to mix the batter together until all of the cornmeal is moistened.
👉🏽Pour the melted butter into the bowl with the batter and mix with a wooden spoon until combined. Do not overmix the batter.
👉🏽Divide the batter evenly among the 12 muffin cups, and bake the cornbread in the preheated oven for 20 to 22 minutes, or until a toothpick inserted into the center of a muffin comes out clean.
👉🏽Allow the cornbread muffins to cool in the pan for about 10 minutes before enjoying.
